>
  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Understanding Apostille for UAE-Bound Documents</h2>
      <p>The UAE is not currently a member of the Hague Apostille Convention. This means documents destined for UAE use require authentication through the traditional legalisation chain, regardless of whether your document's country of origin is a Hague member.</p>

      <p>For documents from Hague-member countries (US, UK, India, Australia, Canada, etc.), the process is: (1) Obtain apostille in the issuing country, (2) UAE Embassy attestation in the issuing country, (3) MOFA/MOFAIC attestation in UAE, and (4) Translation if required.</p>

      <p>For documents from non-Hague countries (Pakistan, Egypt, Jordan, Lebanon, etc.), the full embassy attestation chain is required: notarisation, home country Ministry of Foreign Affairs, UAE Embassy, then MOFA in UAE.</p>

      <p>While an apostille from a Hague-member country simplifies the first step of authentication, it does not eliminate the need for UAE Embassy and MOFA attestation.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

